{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"caf35b3c-7cfc-4c8d-a557-c8382b822bd4","content":"It's a straightforward change. In your project file, either **remove** the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property or set it to `false`:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\nThat's it — `MSTest.Sdk` defaults to **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** when `UseVSTest` is not set (or is `false`).\n\n### Key differences to be aware of:\n\n1. **Running tests** — use `dotnet test` as usual; it works with both runners.\n2. **CLI output** — the new platform has a different console output format. You can customize it with `--output` options.\n3. **`.runsettings`** — still supported, but some VSTest-specific adapter settings may need updating.\n4. **CI pipelines** — if you rely on VSTest-specific TRX loggers or arguments (`--logger trx`), add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package:\n   ```xml\n   <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"*\" />\n   ```\n5. **Code coverage / other extensions** — VSTest data collectors are replaced by platform extensions (e.g., `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`).\n\nAfter the change, run `dotnet test` to verify everything works.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5177ae22-c4ac-44aa-b375-2d992c8db567","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"9822:1230E4:1780A4:1EC868:69FFD85C"},"id":"ef2d1fd2-4b6b-41c0-9480-c57494619501","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:59:18.545Z","parentId":"879eea34-7ed5-496e-b812-e592b611e2bf"}
